        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         PartyBid makes NFTs more social, with a literal party upfront and the opportunity for hundreds of people to buy, own, and manage expensive NFTs together in the back. Its social nature is obvious from its website, which feels as if
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ_msjQURWHBYjbzGoSf4iWjYBDH-PbD1cUkTZvmpD35jjMV51wuteW9kk_T9dpQJTz3BWvFQo4di45ewchEzwdJvBo8CC5I3HUoiKuJi6rlQLIddonO1JjTfUEp4-StjJhksDxQx5kMAAEnFOjsKOmENAyPrzl8xORQ4S-WKycki3rXuu2v_uvFvlud59mFOK-mc3ltO4mKUQZUUAmMwzB20AUuB0B0LEgHzjDBLE6jF8CFGNDx10DXmXX7Yfdq3M_nEykq5WpziWlu8s_brLjcQuPRba5HivXSmIxd0D-o9UnshtczJiwtSa9NvXPi0HMQFPoHrWXRy0kA6wVpzj63q_Rv-gdiRIH_" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Figma
         </a>
         and
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUctuwyAQ_Bpzq8XTwQcOjaoee-kHWBg2DooBi0et_H1xErUSWqSd3Z3dGaMLLDHd1RZzQUeYyn0DFWDPK5QCCdUMaXJWkYFKJviIrOKWSCGRy9MlAXjtVlVSBbTVeXVGFxfDowNjKtC1dY7iBFwwsJoNMyEWAxhujZWUjGJ88upqHQQDCn4g3WMAtKprKVvu2HtHP9vb9733Orel9phuuXfxyLPPWvyUY00GOvYRYpljcmHp6HAAHqyr_gD-TnohRvtNuyU0TL7RN0pe-VZx1H_F0tHz-TXr_F3nbJKbIWXkFMWUYIlHQgXhQ0_6ixg5aVfRy2iI0VTSGU6DlURIycGIjmO_0D63KUWbW2-iR0n9L8vx7ao9rA-g6Ti139fgyn2CoOcV7FPi8nTqIfq0QIDUHLSTLg9_BGGCSEzYU9LmARtPklAmUWO2sXWFf9JffCCsCw" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Masterworks
         </a>
         had a baby, with cursors and comments flying around the site in real-time. As Friday\xe2\x80\x99s auction went on, hundreds of people, represented by moving cursors and emojis, visibly zoomed around the site. It\xe2\x80\x99s hard to describe in words; you can see it in the image above, and you should
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ_msjSAoLhgMZt5DcNP9ZJRIFDH-PbD1cUkTZv2pDk5nzMIayqXzqki-bQZrww6wlk3QIRCjgplDl6zgateiol4LTxTUpFQ56UA7CZsGssBJB92C85gSPH-oJRL8m6Tj9w7Zek4ioGNDqTwxk2WT2wQi398zeEDRAcafqFcKQLZ9Bsx11f_9eLfrc7z7LIpeNngO5NzO33WAJUEzSlnVNGJccnE0LFukZNgAI4vk2POcMUtjINXTColwMmXoPvKu3rYisb9dC7tpOiY0KYS4trkn7fZYbuFlmxucz9iwGuGaOwG_gmND7sbw7xChNKY-tngTUyyXjJFWf-EbFT6aVSM94o0Z5_aV_w3_QOqpIWw" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          check it out by visiting yourself
         </a>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Like a Zombie, NFTs were supposed to be dead. What\xe2\x80\x99s going on?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I have a theory.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         On Thursday night, I went on
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2uhCAMhZ9mWBpAUFywuJt5DcNPccgoGKh34ttfRhc3ado0TXt6PmcQllxOveeK5JtmPHfQCT51BUQo5KhQ5ug1G7jqpZiI18IzJRWJdQ4FYDNx1VgOIPth1-gMxpyuDUq5JC89OGfd4Kcx2CC88daIYHqQPow0MGZvXXP4CMmBhl8oZ05AVv1C3Ouj_3nwZwv8xO9Hnctb62qJxWxvEjWnnFFFJ8YlE0PHuiAnwQAcD5NjznDFLYyDV0wqJcDJh6Dbwrt62IrGvb8HSdEpo80lpqWN3y-zwXoNmqm51e1IEc8ZkrEr-Nsv3tguAvMCCUrD6WeDFyzJeskUZf3trwHpp1Ex3ivSlH1uW-lf9A-7h4V7" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Sriram Krishnan
         </a>
         and
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ_msjSUH8UFi9nMaxiEqmQUDNa58e2Hq4tJmjZN056ezzvCOZfL7vkg9kkDXTvahO9jRSIs7DywDDFYaIWRWvUsWBXAaMPiMUwFcXNxtVROZPs5rtE7ijndG5wLzRZrRM8dephCFyZU0HoFQUplOuTSYPfoujNETB4t_mK5ckK22oVoP17y6yW-a9A7fj5qfN5q51yhJRYWreACuOE9CA2qbaCZdK8A0Yup9-CdMGLErg0GtDEKvX4pvs2iOc7xIOd_PgdZsSnTmEtMcx3_LG7D9R5UU0Ot25kiXQMmN64YHr_0YLsJDDMmLBVnGBzdsDRIDYaDfPxVILLvDAhpWFUOuW6lf9E_HdWD-g" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Aarthi Ramamurthy
         </a>
         \xe2\x80\x99s
         <em>
          Good Time Show
         </em>
         on Clubhouse to discuss the *Metaverse* with\xc2\xa0 Gabby Dizon (YieldGuild), 3LAU, Donnie Dinch (Bitski), Jarrodd Dicker (The Chernin Group), Jon Lai (a16z), and Jesse Walden (Variant).
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Not Boring readers will be very familiar with the Metaverse at this point. We\xe2\x80\x99ve been talking about it for months and months. I\xe2\x80\x99m guilty of tying anything that could conceivably be tied to the Metaverse to the Metaverse.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Over the past few weeks, the Metaverse has gone mainstream. Matthew Ball published his
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuhTAMRVfzMisiPwiDDDrpNlA-BqIHCUrMQ-y-KQwqWbZs6-raxxmEOeVL76kg-UsjXjvoCGdZAREyOQrkMXhNO6a4FAPxWniqpCKhjFMG2ExYNeYDyH7YNTiDIcVb0bZMkkVDz4SV3FA1OOUd74T1xg5cSTb1PYjH1xw-QHSg4QP5ShHIqhfEvbz494v91DjPs9kM4gKnNevafFwd1u5rAzRVVOBrz2GrNwfNWkZb1Q6USSq6hjaTHAQFcGwaHHWGKWah77yiUikBTr5Eu82sKYctaNy7cWkjWceENuUQ57p-L2aD9V7UR8datyMGvEaIxq7gHwb4oLypjDNEyBWxHw3eACXlkqqW8ufnCokPvaKMK1Kdfaqq-G_6C62Yi7o" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          9-part series
         </a>
         . Satya Nadella talked about the enterprise Metaverse (sounds fun!). Zuck and Co have said \xe2\x80\x9cmetaverse\xe2\x80\x9d a million times over the past couple weeks. Ben Thompson wrote a
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQhU_TLA2_DS5YzGauYRBKJa1goJyJtx_UxSSECvXyeFWfdwhzLqfdc0VyXQOeO9gEv3UFRCjkqFCGGCx7cyOU7EmwMjCjDIl1mArA5uJqsRxA9mNco3cYc7odlHJFFqsnpdQk9CioMYEzJbUJvQYdtKHUhSfXHSFC8mDhB8qZE5DVLoh7fYmvF_9up2Jp4_qlyZ3PW-twylkrG6Brpgq1PUi0V5sa2jOumHx3rJtULxmA51PvmXfc8BH0OximjJHg1UvSbeZdPcaKzn-u30mxKeOYS0xzkz-L22C9hbbl0Op2pIjnAMmNK4QHAD4cbyTDDAmugcPg8KanmFDMUCaehRsh0WvDuDCkJYfcXOk_9A_txYhn" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          piece on the Metaverse
         </a>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         NFTs will clearly play a role in the Metaverse. When everything is digital, proving that you own something and being able to bring it with you across the internet will be key. But this isn\xe2\x80\x99t a Metaverse piece. It\xe2\x80\x99s a social network piece.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         At one point in the
         <em>
          Good Time Show
         </em>
         conversation,
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM-OhCAMxp9mOBr-Kh447GVfgyBUhx0FA3Unvv0yetikadM07dfv5x3Ckstp9lyRfJLFcweT4F1XQIRCjgrFxmBYz7VQciTByMC00iRWOxeAzcXVYDmA7Me0Ru8w5nRtUMoVeZphdIMD2js6U1AD94IL7Wc5C3CeqvHWdUeIkDwY-IVy5gRkNU_EvT7E14N_t8B3_HzU-by17seVkkOI_tWejIZTzqimI-OKyb5j3axGyQA8n0fPvOOaTzD0QTOltQSvHpJuC-_qMVV0_vW5SopJGadcYlra-PV0G6zXoDmzrW5HinhaSG5aIdym8WZ3YbALJCiNabAOL2KKCcU0ZeI22aiIcdCsASBNOeS2lf5F_wArtoYo" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Jarrod Dicker
         </a>
         brought up the importance of community and status in web3 and it triggered a high kid thought:
         <strong>
          NFTs tick a lot of the boxes of a successful social network from Eugene Wei\xe2\x80\x99s
         </strong>
         <em>
          <strong>
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOhCAQRb-m2bXh2eCCxWzmNwyP0iatYADb-PeDupik4BIqVbfqOFNhSvnQayoVnddQjxV0hL3MUCtktBXIQ_CavKhigvfIa-6JEgqFMowZYDFh1jVvgNbNzsGZGlK8KjCmAr01l2LEIxFWKuVkb0ZhJJFSWaZGyxm9fc3mA0QHGr6QjxQBzfpd61oe7OdBf1vs-97BNkEbDkLn0tL-7JymJhST_pR2rkeppm7laVo82_zf4AAFTTElWOGeUEH4qyPdKHpOABwde0ecoYpakC-viFCKgxMPjpeJdmWzraH7nJ4o65iqTTnEqaU_b7PAfCXa9kPTZYuhHgNEY2fwN5h6871QDecCuXH3g6kXVUGYIAoTdoNo5FgvFaFMoebsU6uK_6Z_uVCPzA" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            Status-as-a-Service
           </a>
          </strong>
         </em>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Before the full Metaverse arrives, there\xe2\x80\x99s already something happening that\xe2\x80\x99s bigger than jpegs. NFTs are starting to feel a lot like a new kind of social network that sits
         <em>
          above
         </em>
         other social networks and communities -- something of a
         <strong>
          Superverse
         </strong>
         -- and there\xe2\x80\x99s no better framework to evaluate a social network than the one Wei put forth in
         <em>
          Status-as-a-Service (StaaS).
         </em>
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          Status-as-a-Service
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <em>
          (If you\xe2\x80\x99ve read and internalized Status-as-a-Service, you can skip this section.)
         </em>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMGuhCAMRb9mWBqK4OCCxdvMbxiE6pBRMFDfxL9_qIuXkJKmae-9x1nCOeXDbKkQO8tAx4Ym4rcsSISZ7QXzELyBTuhWyZ55Iz1opVkow5QRVxsWQ3lHtu3jEpylkOK1wblQ7G3A6-kpOy46Ca3qEbDTfrQKxtY5h_LWtbsPGB0a_MV8pIhsMW-irTzan4d41UffcDpqXFprh_uM1SYGFozgArjmPQgFsmugmVQvAdGJqXfgrNBixGfnNSitJTr1kHydRVP2sZB1n_MkyyYmGlMOca7jz9uuuFyDGmuo_7rHQMeA0Y4L-jsx3eAuBsPpJ1egfrB04VI1LmgO7Z2wImn7pwbRalaVfapb8V_0DzCrhMM" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Eugene Wei
         </a>
         , a former product leader at Amazon, Hulu, Flipboard, and Oculus, is one of the best tech essayists on the internet. Practically everything he writes becomes canon, and
         <em>
          Status-as-a-Service
         </em>
         , which he wrote in February 2019, might be his greatest contribution.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The piece makes Not Boring seem short. It comes in at a whopping 19,825 words. If you haven\xe2\x80\x99t read it, I highly recommend that
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOhCAQRb-m2bXh2eCCxWzmNwyP0iatYADb-PeDupik4BIqVbfqOFNhSvnQayoVnddQjxV0hL3MUCtktBXIQ_CavKhigvfIa-6JEgqFMowZYDFh1jVvgNbNzsGZGlK8KjCmAr01l2LEIxFWKuVkb0ZhJJFSWaZGyxm9fc3mA0QHGr6QjxQBzfpd61oe7OdBf1vs-97BNkEbDkLn0tL-7JymJhST_pR2rkeppm7laVo82_zf4AAFTTElWOGeUEH4qyPdKHpOABwde0ecoYpakC-viFCKgxMPjpeJdmWzraH7nJ4o65iqTTnEqaU_b7PAfCXa9kPTZYuhHgNEY2fwN5h6871QDecCuXH3g6kXVUGYIAoTdoNo5FgvFaFMoebsU6uK_6Z_uVCPzA" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          you do so
         </a>
         , but for now, I\xe2\x80\x99ll summarize a few of the main points that are relevant to this piece.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Wei begins with two principles:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <em>
            People are status-seeking monkeys
           </em>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <em>
            People seek out the most efficient path to maximizing social capital
           </em>
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Even though those are uncontroversial statements, Wei argues that we don\xe2\x80\x99t analyze social networks through the dimension of status or social capital. Money is easier -- there are numbers, and what gets measured gets analyzed -- but, he says (emphasis mine):
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           Social capital is, in many ways, a
           <strong>
            leading indicator of financial capital
           </strong>
           , and so its nature bears greater scrutiny. Not only is it good investment or business practice, but
           <strong>
            analyzing social capital dynamics can help to explain all sorts of online behavior that would otherwise seem irrational
           </strong>
           .
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Less than 1,000 words into his piece and two full years before NFT mania, Wei unknowingly laid the groundwork for analyzing what\xe2\x80\x99s happening. NFTs blur the lines between social and financial capital, and as the media has been quick to point out, buying jpegs for thousands or millions of dollars seems irrational.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The mistake that those who dismiss NFTs make is the same that Wei argued people were making in analyzing social networks:
         <strong>
          missing the importance of social capital
         </strong>
         . Traditionally, people have used Metcalfe\xe2\x80\x99s Law to explain the network effects powering social networks: \xe2\x80\x9cThe value of a telecommunications network is proportional to the square of the number of connected users of the system (n^2).\xe2\x80\x9d The more users a social network has, according to Metcalfe\xe2\x80\x99s Law, the more valuable it is to every new user.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The problem was, Metcalfe\xe2\x80\x99s Law didn\xe2\x80\x99t perfectly explain what was happening in the real world. Metcalfe\xe2\x80\x99s Law alone would predict that whichever network got big first would continue to build up an increasingly insurmountable lead by being the most valuable to each new user. But Facebook took down MySpace, and Instagram and Snapchat stole younger users\xe2\x80\x99 attention from Facebook. People\xe2\x80\x99s preferences aren\xe2\x80\x99t captured so cleanly.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         It wasn\xe2\x80\x99t that network effects and Metcalfe\xe2\x80\x99s Law were wrong, it was just that they didn\xe2\x80\x99t capture the reasons that someone might use a social network beyond pure utility, so Wei proposed a new framework for analyzing social networks\xe2\x80\x99 strength that added social capital to the mix.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
